  • Only CML will have the philadelphia chromosome.
  • In CML, the non blast cells will reflect the underlying CML
    • They will show neutrophilia with a left shift and basophilia. Source

      The commonest mutation in AML is FLT3. Source
    • To complicate things, b cells require two signals from the Th cell to become activated. There is also a less potent form of b cell activation - T cell independent activation which is dependent on B cell receptor crosslinking by antigents - but this method is less potent. (And no memory B cells are formed by this method Source )
    • once activated, they will produce IgG / M/ D etc. (rather than their naive state IgM). This is called isotype switching or class switching
      • Plasma cells cannot switch classes, cannot act as antigen presenting cells and cannot take up antigen.

Mnemonic: Catch the 9:22 train to philadelphia (clock - chronic)

Renal involvement is one of the commonest complications of multiple myeloma.(50% incidence!)

  1. Cast nephropathy: Light chains -> freely filtered at glomerulus -> resorbed but resorbtive capacity exceeded in MM -> precipitate in the tubule in combination with Tamm-horsfall proteins-> cast nephropathy. Usually presents as Acute or subacute kidney injury.

"LCDD must be differentiated from AL amyloidosis. LCDD is Congo red negative and is usually IF positive for rather than light chain. Moreover, in LCDD the deposits are subendothelial and granular, whereas in amyloidosis they are composed of randomly arranged fibrils."

[!TIP] mnemonic: causes of MCD -> "minimal" = "invisible on LM" -> causes are I's

  • Idiopathic, Iatrogenic,Invasion (Malignancy),Infection, Industry (Mercury)

Causes of MCD:
- Need to exclude hepatitis B, SLE, thyroiditis, some drugs (penicillamine, gold / mercury, captopril, NSAIDS) and malignancy.

Therefore, Type 2 is a defect of 'bicarbonate reabsorption'.

Type 1 = H+ secretion defect in DCT.


Causes of papilloedema

  • space-occupying lesion: neoplastic, vascular
  • malignant hypertension
  • idiopathic intracranial hypertension
  • hydrocephalus
  • hypercapnia

Rare causes include

  • hypoparathyroidism and hypocalcaemia
  • vitamin A toxicity

mechanics deal with lots of viscous fluids -> macroglobinaemia.
W in Waldenstrom -> M in IgM
Macro means large -> macro spleen and liver and macro lymph nodes
[!INFO] hyperviscosity syndrome (HVS)
The clinical presentation in HVS consists principally of the triad of

  1. **mucosal bleeding,
  2. visual changes,
  3. and neurologic symptoms**.
    [3, 4] Constitutional symptoms and cardiorespiratory symptoms may also occur.Source
  • damage to small blood vessels - nose and gums bleeding;
  • Ig accumulates in LN, spleen, liver. -> #hepatosplenomegaly and #lymphadenopathy

Multi-system autoimmune disorder with dysregulation of fibrogenesis. Pathophysiology not completely explained.
Chronic endothelial damage with IL-2 producing cells migrating into the tissues because of increased expression of adhesion molecules.
Limited cutaneous scleroderm is also known as CREST syndroome (passMedicine)
ACA (anti-centromere antibodies) present in most.
- Beak like nose and microstomia
- telangiectasiaa and dilated nail fold capillary loops.
Antitopoisomerase (anti-Scl-70) and anti-RNA polymerase
antibodies.
